In the military, '''dwell time''' is the amount of time that service members spend in their home station between deployments to war zones. Dwell time is designed to allow service members a mental and physical break from combat and to give them time with their families. It is an important component of long term military readiness.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.webb.senate.gov/issuesandlegislation/armedservicesandveterans/Dwell_Time.cfm | title=Ensuring Appropriate Dwell Time and Rotational Cycles | publisher=[[United States Senate]] | accessdate=December 6, 2012 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121212110348/http://www.webb.senate.gov/issuesandlegislation/armedservicesandveterans/Dwell_Time.cfm | archivedate=December 12, 2012 | df= }}</ref>
==History== From the early days of the Global War on Terrorism until 2011, dwell time for American service members was reduced to a maximum of 12 months for most service members:<ref>{{cite web|last=Larson|first=Mark|title=Dwelling on Dwell Time|url=http://atwar.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/06/29/dwelling-on-dwell-time/|work=New York Times|publisher=At War Blog|accessdate=6 December 2012|date=June 29, 2011}}</ref> "Dwell time at home stations became nothing more than getting ready for the next deployment."<ref>{{cite press_release | url=http://www.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=118706 | title=Leader Engagement Key to ‘Bridging Basics,’ Battaglia Says | publisher=American Forces Press Service | date=Dec 4, 2012 | accessdate=December 6, 2012}}</ref> In October, 2011, the [[United States Department of Defense]] extended dwell time for U.S. soldiers to 24 months for every year deployed to a war zone.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tan|first=Michelle|title=Dwell time increases to 2 years next month|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2011/09/army-dwell-time-increases-to-2-years-090411w/|accessdate=6 December 2012|newspaper=Army Times|date=4 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thebatt.com/news/dwell-time-for-military-to-change-1.1277831#.UMBjj4PXaGo | title=‘Dwell time’ for military to change |work=The Battalion | date=July 25, 2012 | accessdate=December 6, 2012 | author=Johnson, Samantha}}</ref>
==Effects== A 2012 study of over 65,000 service members found that longer periods at home between deployments reduced the incidence of [[post traumatic stress disorder]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=MacGregor, Andrew J.|author2=Peggy P. Han|author3=Amber L. Dougherty|author4=Michael R. Galarneau|last-author-amp=yes|title=Effect of Dwell Time on the Mental Health of US Military Personnel With Multiple Combat Tours|journal=American Journal of Public Health|year=2012|volume=102|issue=S1|pages=A55-A59|doi=10.2105/ajph.2011.300341}}</ref> Another study found that longer dwell times were associated with a reduced risk of suicide.<ref>{{cite news|title=When Warriors Hurt Themselves|newspaper=New York Times|date=2 Sep 2010|pages=A34}}</ref>
